== Carbon Cycle

Fossil carbon consists of the coal, diamonds, graphite, petroleum, natural gas,
and etc. These came from the decay of organic matter that were buried down in
time. These carbon can then escape into the surface by human excavation or by
weathering.

When carbon is burned, it will evolve into the atmosphere as carbon dioxide.
And this gas will be absorbed by plants and algae via photosynthesis. These
plants that can use carbon dioxide and produce their own energy from the sun's
radiation are called _autotrophs_. And they are at the highest energy level.
The _heterotrophs_ on the other hand are those that rely on other species for
their sustenance.

== Oxygen Cycle

Plants release oxygen from photosynthesis. Most organisms on earth rely on
oxygen to live by means of cellular respiration. The decay of organic matter
also requires oxygen.

Oxygen is an _oxidizing agent_. These sets of elements or compounds are able to
form radicals. That is why some say that oxygen is a killer especially as we
get older the amount of oxygen we breathe accumulates.

== Nitrogen Cycle

_Nitrfying bacteria_ turn the ammonia from decomposing organic matter into
nitrites and then into nitrates. _Nitrogen fixation_ on the other hand produces
ammonium. And these compounds are useful to human life as these get
_assimilated_ to living beings as nutrition. Nitrogen is an essential element
of proteins after all. And the cycle continues by death and decay.

A problem exists in bodies of water where excess amounts of nitrogen are
accumulating. This is called _eutrophication_ where the flora blooms rapidly
thus decreasing the levels of oxygen in the body of water. On the other hand,
bodies of water with a deficiency in nitrogen are called _dead zones_.

== Sulfur Cycle

Sulfur is a part of fossil. It is grouped with the elements that come from
decomposition of organic matter such as carbon and nitrogen. From decay, it will
turn into sulfates, and its runoff can then turn to sulfuric acid. An example
is acid rain.

= Atmospheric Dynamics and Meterology

A question that is important in air pollution control is "Where will the
pollutants go?" It is important to know that no 100% separate pollutants, and
some go away to disperse or accumulate in the atmosphere. This is where
atmospheric dynamics and meteorology come into play.

== Difference between Atmospheric Dynamics and Meterology

Atmospheric dynamics focus more on the long term effects and rely on physical
laws to make predictions. However, meteorology focuses more on day to day
weather.

== What is an Air Parcel?

An air parcel is a theoretical bubble of air used by meteorologists to explain
weather phenomena. They study the behavior of vertical transport of air parcels
and what happens to its temperature when it expands or compresses.

== Temperature Inversion

Warm air tends to rise and cold air tends to sink. _Temperature_ (or _thermal_)
inversion results when the layer cold air sits on top of warm air. In effect,
pollutants are trapped since air cannot escape through the layer of warm air.
Normally the ground is warm and the temperature decreases as altitude increases
atleast in the troposphere.

